log.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">evidence given here is all</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> my own p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ersonal evidence.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Co</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">m</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">bining segregation and integration</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Committee</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> is bound to hear a great deal a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">bout segregation.  S</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">egregation has a place (particularly routes to schools) to encourage the large number of potential cyclists fearful of cycling on the r</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">oads.  However segregation is no panacea and is certainly no quick fix solution.  It is often overlooked that even the Dutch do not just do segregation and that they do integration better than we do.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">My own observations over the summer were that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Paris, a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">city in which there were zero cycling deaths last year</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> has a great deal of integration and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> very</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> little segregation.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Unfortunately some cycling advocates regard </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the calling for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">improved conditions for cycling on the roads as heretical </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">since</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> it is seen to detract from the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ir</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> goal of segregation.  This plays into the hands of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">minority of motorists who are hostile to the notion of sharing the roads with cyclists and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> who</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> wish the lat</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">er to be put out of their way.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Potential cyclists are fear</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ful not of the roads </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">per se</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> but of the badly driven motor vehicles on the roads.  Few complete journeys will be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">capable of being </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">made </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">wholly </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">on segregated infrastructure of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">an appropriate quality and so people</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> will not take to their bicycles in large numbe</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">rs unless the conditions for cyclists on the roads are also addressed.  I will therefore focus my evidence on that issue.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">On-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">road infrastructure</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The general quality of this is very poor indeed.  Cycle lanes very rarely meet the design requirements of the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> DfT’s </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Cycle Infrastructure Design (Local Transport Note 2/08) in relation to such important matters as lane width</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.  Furthermore</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> advance stopped lines are routinely ignored.</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Even the ‘flagship’ Cycle Super Highways in London rely</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> heavily upon 1.5m wide lanes which are counterproductive because they are too narrow for cyclists seeking to comply with </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">B</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ikeability training as to road positioning.  </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">As I learnt when representing the family of Brian Dorling at his Inquest, Bow roundabout</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> is a bad example of how a strip of blue paint on the nearside of a traffic lane induces cyclists into the worst possible conflict with left turning lorries.  </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">I have written to the Highways Department o</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">f</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Hounslow Borough Council in relation to the designs </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">for the proposed Cycle Super Highway 9 but, very typically, my submissions have been ignored.  The </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">designers</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> of our on</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">road cycling infrastructure </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ignore</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Cycle Infrastructure Design and</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> follow a philosophy of getting cyclists </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">out of the way</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.  This encour</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ages</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the dangerous assumption that cyclists should </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">keep to</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the nearside of other traffic (even when cycle speeds exceed average ve</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">hicle speeds)</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">  The</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> designers</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ignore the views of cyclists and cycling bodies.  This needs to change.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">he </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">common assumption</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> that cyclists should be out of the way on the extreme nearside margins of the road</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> is already corrected in cycle training.  It is just as important that it is c</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">hallenged by </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">making</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">principles</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> of Bikeability part of standard driving instruction and test</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and required study for all Highway Engineers and designers.  None of the designers of the CSH2 through Bow Roundabout had undertaken Bikeability level 3.  The highest level achieved by a designer was level 1 which does not require leaving the playgroun</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">d.</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Joined-up Government</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Responsibility for encouraging cycling is spread broadly across many agencies.  What is really required at every level is a cultural shift from the tradition of putting the interests of motorists first.  This is frequently acknow</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ledged in words but seldom in actions.  Even at the top level the Department for Transport opened a consultation in respect of the speed limits of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">heavy </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">lorries on single carriageway roads, apparently overlooking the obvious impact this would have on cycli</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">sts.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Speed limits</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">/lorry bans </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> and other calming measures</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Reducing speed limits in urban streets to 20 mph would be a big step towards making cycling on the roads actually and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">subjectively</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> safer.  In most urban environments at most times motorised traffic does not exceed an average of 20 mph anyway so the limit would serve to rein back the surges between traffic lights without a significant adverse effect on vehicle flow or journey times.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Traffic lights could also be designed to allow ‘waves’ (including cyclists) through at around 18 mph.  Through motorised traffic could be prevented from using select route</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> by placing </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">removable bollards across the road.  There has been far more talk than a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ction over 20 mph speed limits, which are not even introduced on the ‘flagship’ Cycle Super Highways.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">It is a very good sign that following the APPCG report the police came at last under ministerial direction to enfo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ce 20 mph speed limits.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Lorry bans ma</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">y help to improve conditions for cyclists but not if they merely push lorries into operating at different times of day.  Not all bicycle journeys are made at rush hour and not all</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> fatalities due to lorries have occurred at these time</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.  Lifting the lorry ba</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">n at night may help spread the load.  Lorries could be banned from popular cycle routes for the entirety or at least the majority of the day.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Far more important than controls on the times that lorries may operate are requirements for mandatory safety equi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">pment on lorries.  These should be made more stringent and exemptions should not be permitted.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Policing bad driving</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Bad driving around cyclists is what makes many fearful of riding on the road.  Close passes, cutting up, mobile telephone use, speeding, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">tailgating and other bad driving behaviour (together with the over-zealous promotion of helmets) all contribute to a subjective feeling that cycling is a hazardous activity.  Near misses put cyclists off ever taking, or returning, to the roads.  Action is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">hardly ever taken against such drivers unless (and even then only sporadically) a collision is caused.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">  The laws are there</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> they are just not adequately enforced.  More is required from the CPS and Courts but most important is the starting point – the poli</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ce.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Some police force</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> have a policy of not prosecuting bad drivers unless injury o</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> damage has resulted.  Even those who do not have such a policy make no serious effort to deter bad driving.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">I spent a morning with the Metropolitan Police Cycle Task For</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ce.  No </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">motorists</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> were stopped for passing too close to cyclists or for encroaching on advanced stop lines</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.  One skip driver was talked to, but let off, for driving down Fulham Road conversing on a hand held mobile telephone.  In the afternoon I had a conv</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ersation with Sergeant Simon Castle of the Task Force who said that motorists were never taken up for close passing because that concept was ‘too subjective’.  He further said that the Taskforce never prosecuted drivers for ignoring advanced stop lines at </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">lights because the consequence of a mandatory 3 points on the licence was ‘disproportionate’ to the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">offence.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">  It seems that the view of the police that they should not enforce ASLs has recently changed for the better in response to political pressure.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">By </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">way of further example, the ACPO lead office on traffic policing, Suzette Davenport</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> has written to all Chief Police Officers suggesting that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">prosecutions of bad driving based upon video evi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">dence should be discouraged.  She </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">claimed to have legal advice tha</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t a conviction based on such evidence would be unlikely (if true</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> this is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> shockingly bad legal advice!).  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Her letter</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> was a reaction to the fact that an ex police officer had found a commercial opportunity</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> (‘Police Witness’)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> in collecting reports of bad driv</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ing backed by film evidence.  This opportunity exists because it is so hard to make </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">reports</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> direct to the police.  Although I understand that Ms Davenport has subsequently largely recanted that advice</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> it remains relied upon by the Traffic Criminal Justice</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Unit (‘TCJU’) of the Metropolitan Police in rejecting complaints of bad driving based upon video evidence.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">A web based reporting system, ‘Roadsafe’, was set up by the Metropolitan Police, which initially invited complaints of bad driving based upon video</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> evidence.  Despite hundred</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, probably thousands, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> well evidenced reports of bad driving backed by video evidence, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">no</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> prosecutions have resulted.  Roadsafe officers have to refer cases they deem to be bad to the TCJU who take no action based upon Ms Dave</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">nport’s advice.  They will also use any spurious excuse to deem the evidence insufficient.  By way of example I filmed very dangerous driving from a lorry clearly marked with a company logo and called out the number plate </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">(which did indeed belong to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> a lorr</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">y operated by that company</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.  Roadsafe explained that they did not take action because the registration plate I had called out was not visible on the film footage</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In response to numerous complaints, Roadsafe </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">has now adopted the line</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> that it was only ever intended ‘to gather </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">information’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">  Their website now solicits reports relating to uninsured drivers (for example) but not bad driving around cyclists.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Although it is acceptable for the police to have some discretion on the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">circumstances of individual cases, they have in fact determined that it is for them to decide whether certain laws, passed by Parliament, are to be enforced at all.  This is in my view, in a democracy, unacceptable and must stop.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">As well </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> great difficu</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">lty in getting the police to take action </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">in cases where</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">there is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> clear evidence of driving without due care, I have also had great difficulty in getting the police to take action when I have been threatened (successful prosecution only after I complained 3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> times about the case being dropped) and even assaulted (police caution given with no reference to me).</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">It is time that offences that harm, endanger or threaten cyclists are treated as seriously aggravated by the type of victim (as occurs, say in the cont</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">exts of domestic violence, racism or homophobia). </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> The response to near misses should be akin to that in the airline industry (or indeed any industry where safety is taken seriously).</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Such offences should be easier to report and should be acted upon unless</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> there is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">good reason not to.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Complaints about the behaviour of cyclists (or sensationalist talk that there is a ‘War on the roads’) should be seen for what they are: a distraction from the real problems.  Of course law breaking by cyclists merits its own</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> proportionate response (just as dealing with drunk holiday makers on aircraft does).  However nobody would allow the behaviour of a minority of passengers to justify inaction over airline safety.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">  There is a far lower KSI rate in airline travel than in cy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">cling and I see this as a legitimate comparison.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In pursuance of the public interest the State encourages individuals to cycle.  It is only right that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> in exchange, those who take up the exhortation receive the benefit of protection from the agents of the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> State.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Summary</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">I have concentrated on giving evidence on what I consider to be most important</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> areas that currently discourage cycling</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.  Riding a bicycle on the road should be an enjoyable </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">subjectively safe experience.  There should be a very low degr</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ee of tolerance for those who make it otherwise.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Suggested </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Recommendations</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Those who design on</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">road cycle facilities must have regard to the Cycle Infrastructure Design Standards and must consult cyclists and cycling organisations.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">They should also have cycle training.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Much public money is squandered because this is not done.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Speed limits, lorry bans and removable bollards preventing through motorised traffic should be introduced on select roads on which cycle use is prioritised.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Lorries must be required to have side bars and cyclist detection equipment and no exemptions from these requirements should be permitted.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Driving instruction and testing must include the principles of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">‘B</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ikeability</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> so that all roadusers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> have an understanding of best cycling technique</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> even if they do not themselves cycle.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Police officers </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">(together with the CPS and the Courts) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">must be encouraged to treat offences which harm, endanger or threaten cyclists as seriously aggravated by the ty</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">pe of victim and consider every potential case on its merits (strength of evidence and public interest) without blanket policies against action.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Police forces</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> should adopt systems which make such</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> offences much easier to report and should provide feedback </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to complainants.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>